in sebaceous glands","Disrupts connections between corneocytes leading to desquamation","Inhibits bacterial growth on the skin surface"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESalicylic acid primarily works through its keratolytic action. \u003Cstrong\u003EDisruption of connections between corneocytes\u003C/strong\u003E occurs through the dissolution of intercellular cement substance, leading to enhanced desquamation of epithelial cells. This makes it effective for conditions involving excess keratin such as acne, warts, and psoriasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other mechanisms described are incorrect, and explain mechanisms that are preferred in the treatment of other dermatological conditions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking melanin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action for skin-lightening agents like hydroquinone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting bacterial growth\u003C/strong\u003E is how topical antibiotics work.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulating collagen production\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action for retinoids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing sebum production\u003C/strong\u003E worsens acne and is not a therapeutic goal in dermatology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Salicylic acid is a beta-hydroxy acid that promotes keratolysis through disruption of corneocyte adhesion.","Salicylic acid is commonly used topically to treat acne, warts, and psoriasis due to its keratolytic properties.","The mechanism of action of salicylic acid involves both anti-inflammatory effects and increased desquamation of epithelial cells."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61209"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14772"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61209"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T16:08:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T16:08:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7463"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75691"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4932"},"attributes":{"emoji":"